Miscreant Git Server
====================

The miscreant git server is an OSS, MIT-licensed git server that is
backed entirely by object storage. This makes it zero-ops, highly
scalable for high concurrency/agentic git workloads and a cost
effective code hosting option.

Quickstart
----------

[Work in Progress] We are working on building deployable binaries,
for now you can build Miscreant from source and add it as a git remote
for your project.

Run the server (requires a Rust toolchain). By default it listens on
127.0.0.1:8470 and stores all data under ./miscreant-data:

    cargo run

From any repository push to the server. Unknown repositories are created
on the first push, so there is no setup step:

    git push http://127.0.0.1:8470/miscreant main

Then clone it back from any other directory:

    git clone http://127.0.0.1:8470/miscreant


Why Miscreant?
--------------
Agents make exceptional use of file systems, and it is increasingly
clear that having access to a versioned remote file system that can
handle conflicts amongst multiple agents concurrently access the same
files is critical.

Miscreant is a low-level implementation of the git HTTP(S) protocol
that allows for concurrent, transactional access to multiple git
repositories backed by object storage. Unlike using an existing Git
hosting solution like GitHub, Miscreant offers no rate limits, UI or
workflow/action integration. It is designed to be extremely cheap to
store enormous amounts of data and serve thousands of concurrent
reqeusts.

Miscreant is not a complete developer product, instead the intention is
to serve as an infrastructure component of other solutions such as
remote file systems and sandbox backends.

Architecture Overview
=====================

Miscreant is a single binary rust server built on [SlateDB](https://slatedb.io)
that speaks the git HTTPs protocol:

